helpdesk-ticket.description:
I am unable to search my email archives. I think they are on “H” drive but I can’t figure out how to retrieve them. I can only view emails back to Feb. 4th of this year.. Not sure what changed to cause my archives to disappear.
Paul Szepi Facilities Maintenance Department Milwaukee School of Engineering Office 414-277-7160 Mobile 414-507-8624
helpdesk-ticket.description-html:
I am unable to search my email archives.  I think they are on “H” drive but I can’t figure out how to retrieve them.  I can only view emails back to Feb. 4th  of this year..  Not sure what changed to cause my archives to disappear. 
 
Paul Szepi
Facilities Maintenance Department
Milwaukee School of Engineering
Office   414-277-7160
Mobile 414-507-8624

helpdesk-note.body:
Hey Paul,
This type of problem can be caused by a few different issues.
Are you able to access your files on the H drive? Perhaps there is an issue with your network mapping of the H drive. If that is the issue, you can follow this guide on how to map a network drive. for the H drive you will need to enter "\\homestore\homedrives$\username" in the "folder" field. Make sure you are connected to the MSOE network or VPN'd in.
Perhaps there was an accidental deletion of your account setting that points to your outlook pst files. If that is the case, follow these directions for attaching a .pst file to your outlook client.
Please let us know if this solved your problem or if you still have issues with this.

The problem I now have is that the main Google account cannot access the MSOE E-mail system with the new password. When attempting to change the password in the POP3 configuration, I receive an error "Unable to establish secure SSL connection to smtp.gmail.com" or "There was a problem communicating with smtp.gmail.com" depending on if I try connecting with SSL enabled or disabled. My work-around for now is to just keep using the old MSOE password, but I would really like to change it for security reasons. Cheers, Bryan

The problem I now have is that the main Google account cannot access the MSOE E-mail system with the new password.  When attempting to change the password in the POP3 configuration, I receive an error "Unable to establish secure SSL connection to smtp.gmail.com"  or "There was a problem communicating with smtp.gmail.com" depending on if I try connecting with SSL enabled or disabled.  My work-around for now is to just keep using the old MSOE password, but I would really like to change it for security reasons.

Cheers,
Bryan

helpdesk-note.body: Hey Helpdesk, so, this is pretty embarrassing, but I think I found the problem. I tried deleting the account and re-adding it as suggested and was able to set up sending mail from my main G-mail account over the MSOE account. However, the same problem came up when trying to set up POP3 to access my MSOE Inbox: no connection could be established. I stumbled upon the Google help page for setting up POP3 and noticed that the recommended server settings for incoming mail is "pop.gmail.com" and not the default "smtp.gmail.com" which was listed from before changing my MSOE password and attempting a new connection to my MSOE E-mail. A quick e-mail to and from my work e-mail confirms that everything works. Maybe a few other people are missing this small detail. ;) Thanks for all your help guys! Cheers, Bryan
helpdesk-note.body-html:
Hey Helpdesk,

so, this is pretty embarrassing, but I think I found the problem.  I tried deleting the account and re-adding it as suggested and was able to set up sending mail from my main G-mail account over the MSOE account.

However, the same problem came up when trying to set up POP3 to access my MSOE Inbox: no connection could be established.  I stumbled upon the Google help page for setting up POP3 and noticed that the recommended server settings for incoming mail is "pop.gmail.com" and not the default "smtp.gmail.com" which was listed from before changing my MSOE password and attempting a new connection to my MSOE E-mail.

A quick e-mail to and from my work e-mail confirms that everything works.  Maybe a few other people are missing this small detail.  ;)

Thanks for all your help guys!

Cheers,
Bryan

helpdesk-ticket.description: Hi Support, When you have a chance, would you please update the library proxy server config file with the following two changes, and then re-start the proxy server so that the changes take effect: [1] Eliminate the extra "http://" in the stanza for the Neonatal Network. The stanza needs to appear as follows. #T Neonatal Network #U http://www.ingentaconnect.com/content/springer/jnn #H www.ingentaconnect.com #DJ ingentaconnect.com [2] Insert the following stanza for the Journal of Digital & Social Media: #T Journal of Digital & Social Media #U http://www.ingentaconnect.com/content/hsp/jdsmm #H www.ingentaconnect.com #DJ ingentaconnect.com Let me know if you have questions. Thanks very much! Gary Shimek Library

#T Neonatal Network

#T Journal of Digital & Social Media
#U http://www.ingentaconnect.com/content/hsp/jdsmm
#H www.ingentaconnect.com
#DJ ingentaconnect.com

Let me know if you have questions.  Thanks very much!

Gary Shimek
Library

helpdesk-ticket.subject: Password Reset for Alumni
helpdesk-ticket.description: I reset my password today following the email mandating the password change. Now I can’t login to my email. Is there a reason why?
helpdesk-ticket.description-html: I reset my password today following the email mandating the password change.  Now I can’t login to my email.  Is there a reason why?

helpdesk-note.body:
Hi Arianne Brown,
Are you having a problem logging in to outlook? If so, this is a pretty common problem. Below is one solution that works almost universally:
The saved outlook password needs to be updated with the current password. One way to do it is to delete the outlook password that the windows previously saved on your laptop. Once it is deleted, when you reopen the outlook, it should ask for password where in you enter the current password.
Follow the steps below in order to deleted the stored old outlook password.
Click the Start button and type-in "Credential Manager". A dialogue box should appear. In the dialogue box, under "Generic Credentials", click the vault that contains the outlook credentials. Click Remove from vault. Hit 'yes' when it asks for the confirmation to delete those credentials. Reopen Outlook. Now you should get a pop-up window asking you to enter your credentials.
Once you enter your current password, your Outlook should get connected to Microsoft Exchange and your inbox should get updated with recent emails
Note that you might also need to delete a credential that is listed as Office.data or something like that. Please let us know if this works for you and if there is anything more we can do for you. Thank you.

helpdesk-note.body:
Hi parksh,
There's a DNS/DHCP attack that appears to be coming from inside the Tower. I've contacted the switch vendor to help us come up with a method to stop this traffic at the port, as the Firewall is here on campus, and these types of attacks are blocked by the network before they get to any other building. This protects the Campus from the Tower, but it does not protect the Tower from the Tower. This would appear to only affect the wireless connections, as I can still see traffic passing normally over wired ports.
I hope to have a response today. Issue: http://helpdesk.msoe.edu/helpdesk/tickets/6685

If you prefer to use and ftp client such as WinSCP that should work as well. Let me know if you run into any issues.
Thanks Mike Timm Issue: http://helpdesk.msoe.edu/helpdesk/tickets/6680

Could you check the port connected to 1202a? The Internet connection is spontaneously dropping and is out for hours on end. Is this because the switch isn't able to handle the traffic associated with the attack?

Is a way to physically detect where an attack is coming from?

Thank you.

~ Hunter Parks
Sent from my iPhone

On Mar 28, 2016, at 12:06 PM, helpdesk <helpdesk@msoe.edu> wrote:

Hi parksh,

There's a DNS/DHCP attack that appears to be coming from inside the Tower. I've contacted the switch vendor to help us come up with a method to stop this traffic at the port, as the Firewall is here on campus, and these types of attacks are blocked by the network before they get to any other building. This protects the Campus from the Tower, but it does not protect the Tower from the Tower. This would appear to only affect the wireless connections, as I can still see traffic passing normally over wired ports.

I hope to have a response today.

helpdesk-ticket.subject: Color printer not working again
helpdesk-ticket.description:
Hello IT:
I am trying to print one color page, but I cannot get the color printer to spit it out.
· I have over $5 on my Raider account so it should not be a problem with having the money to print with.
· My computer says that the print job was sent to follow you printing so there does not appear to be a problem with my computer though I did see the word hidden in brackets: i.e. [hidden]. Why would it say that? Does that mean anything?
· The color printer creates a test sheet when I power it off and on again, so there is ink and the machine can print.
Honestly guys, this color printer has been a regular source of problems all year. Can we please get this figured out once and for all or find another solution?
Any help would be greatly appreciated!
Thank you,
Sarah Rowell, MLIS Librarian I MSOE Walter Schroeder Library 414-277-7389 rowell@msoe.edu<mailto:rowell@msoe.edu>

helpdesk-note.body:
I uninstalled Follow You on Morpheus and Printers on her laptop and reinstalled Follow you on Printers. Sent a color job twice and when we swiped at the color printer it did not change from the Ready message and the reader did not change color. Both times I checked the black and white and it didn't show a job in her queue. No weird DNS settings.
Tony said he was able to ping the printer and send test pages.
Called Sheila Barber, she said there is invalid card read count on her account since I went over.
Verified her current ID is the one she is using. Asked her to try taking card out of wallet and scanning it alone. She will call back.

-------- Original message -------- From: "Rowell, Sarah" <rowell@msoe.edu> Date: 5/9/16 3:13 PM (GMT-06:00) To: Helpdesk <helpdesk@msoe.edu> Cc: "Kann, Jason" <kann@msoe.edu> Subject: Unable to print in color
Hello IT,
I have just spoken with Sheila Barber, whom I was told was checking my account regarding the discrepancy between what your department and student accounts says I have in credit on my Raider account (which is perhaps why my color print jobs are sent but not actually being printed?) Sheila said I have money on my account and that the problem is on IT’s end. I just added even more money today so I should have sufficient funds to draw from.
The ball appears to be back in your court. I am trying to be patient, but this has gone on for a while now and I would really like to be able to print in color myself instead of asking co-workers to do it for me. If they can print in color, why can’t I?
Also, I have not heard any kind of explanation for why the color printer occasionally prints out several more copies of a sent color document than was requested. Could an instance of that be the reason why your records indicated that my account was overdrawn?
Please let me know if there is anything I can do to facilitate the progress of this ticket. Thomas S. has been very helpful in trying to figure this out, but I feel perhaps this needs to be seen by the next tier of IT and Sheila suggested it would fall under Jason’s purview.
Thank you very much for your assistance with this matter,
Sarah Rowell, MLIS Librarian I MSOE Walter Schroeder Library 414-277-7389 rowell@msoe.edu

helpdesk-ticket.subject: Windows Copy Not Genuine
helpdesk-ticket.description: I am currently studying abroad in Germany with the FHL-MSOE exchange program. A few of the students over here are getting a popup message "This copy of Windows is not genuine", as well as the background changing to black. Attached is a picture of the popup.
helpdesk-ticket.description-html: I am currently studying abroad in Germany with the FHL-MSOE exchange program. A few of the students over here are getting a popup message "This copy of Windows is not genuine", as well as the background changing to black. Attached is a picture of the popup.

helpdesk-note.body:
Hi Garret,
This is likely caused by having your computer away from the MSOE network for so long. Your computer needs to periodically pull validation information from a server here. You should be able to solve this by connecting to the MSOE domain through our VPN, GlobalProtect, and revalidating Windows. If you don't have GlobalProtect, you can follow these instructions: https://community.msoe.edu/docs/DOC-1889 GlobalProtect can be a bit temperamental the first time you try to connect through it, just bear with it. After you have established the connection, you'll want to open your Start menu, right-click Computer, and select Properties. On the bottom right of the window that opens, there should be a link or button to Validate (or Activate) Windows; click it. It should connect through the internet and and validate your copy of Windows. I would recommend restarting your computer after success.
If this does not work, I would suggest trying it on an independent internet connection, not at school (e.g. Starbucks). If it still does not work, we might need to run slmgr commands through command prompt. This is best done over live communication, but can still be issued over email.
Hopefully this solves the problem. If it does, please spread the solution to students who are also suffering from this problem. If it does not, please let us know so we can help you take further steps.
Thank You,
Bryan Voss Tier 2 Technician, IT Help Desk (414) 277-7288
Issue: http://helpdesk.msoe.edu/helpdesk/tickets/6727

Thanks in advance, JaLisa Anderson

helpdesk-note.body:
Hi Nick,
To get an html link to your shared calendar you will you need to publish it via webmail.
To publish a calendar using a html link do the following 1. Open the shared mailbox in webmail. Here is a link on how to open a shared mailbox https://community.msoe.edu/docs/DOC-3870 2. Goto calendars and select options (gear in top right corner) 3. Select publish calendar on the left and then select permission level and save. 4. You will be provided with an html link to the calendar I don't think anyone else on campus is doing this so you may want to test out the link prior to putting it in your newsletter. Let me know if you have any questions Mike Timm

helpdesk-ticket.subject: Alumni email on Android phone
helpdesk-ticket.description:
Hello,
Recently MSOE sent out that alumni email needed a new password. Since doing this I now am getting all alumni email addresses as contacts even though I have this sync option turned off and set to NOT sync. You can imagine when searching to add a contact to a text, it is really hard now that all the alumni are showing in the list.
Is there any way to manually or automatically remove these from the phone? I am unable to find this option and can only say not to sync.
I am running the Verizon Motorola Droid Turbo.
Thanks, Travis Hoffman

helpdesk-note.body:
Hi Travis Hoffman, While not having the same model of phone as you, I believe I can give you a rough idea as to how to stop this from occurring. - I open my phone's settings and scroll to Contacts under the Applications group. - I select Contacts to Display - I am given a list of all apps and places that contacts can come from - I deselect the Outlook app (or whichever email app you prefer) from this list - If you are not using the Microsoft Outlook app, perhaps consider using it Thank You,
Bryan Voss Tier 2 Technician, IT Help Desk (414) 277-7288 Issue: http://helpdesk.msoe.edu/helpdesk/tickets/6738

I went over today and looked over what she had.
Issue: The most recent back up is on the H drive. I opened it and was able to view the correct emails that she wasn't able to see before. The NEW ALLEMAIL was never imported. only ALLEMAIL is imported (and view able from webmail). opening this data file caused outlook to crash or act slow. WIFI in room was very weak signal. Ethernet cable was not plugged in fully and is broken.
I formulated a plan of action to resolve the issue:
1. Remove all old email .pst files from her outlook. 2. Import NEW ALLEMAIL .pst into Outlook to her inbox as folders. 3. Clean up all old .pst files on H and D drives. 4. Repair network cable. 5. Repair VGA connector.
I walked her through this solution and explained the new email servers vs the old ones. She was okay with this resolution.
We scheduled to work on this issue on Thursday May 5th at 11am.

The teacher of the class who runs the blackboard page must remove the student from the class. If the student is getting re-addded to the class, then the student has not yet dropped the class. helpdesk-ticket.subject: Password stops synching
helpdesk-ticket.description: Every week I cannot connect to the wireless and it asks me to enter my credentials. I enter the same password I have been using all week long and it tells me it is incorrect. After this, Windows asks me to verify my credentials by logging out. After doing this, I get locked out trying the password that allowed me to log in to the computer (I understand the windows password is local but why would it change when I log in). helpdesk-note.body:
Hi alis, Issue: http://helpdesk.msoe.edu/helpdesk/tickets/6808
The username is: administrator The password is: System1
This will get you into the local administrator account. The general solution is to have a helpdesk worker add this computer back in. Turning off the computer will turn off GlobalProtect and should eliminate the Trust Relationship issue. If you connect to GlobalProtect after then you should be able to install Matlab from there, provided you do not re-lock the computer. You may also need to update the password in GlobalProtect to your most recent domain one. To do so you open GlobalProtect and under the settigns tab there should be a place to update your password. Let us know if this works.
James Windorff Helpdesk Technician helpdesk@msoe.edu 414 277 7288

On Tue, 5 Apr at 2:35 pm , helpdesk <helpdesk@msoe.edu> wrote:
Hi alis,

Issue: http://helpdesk.msoe.edu/helpdesk/tickets/6808

The username is: administrator
The password is: System1

This will get you into the local administrator account.
The general solution is to have a helpdesk worker add this computer back in. 
Turning off the computer will turn off GlobalProtect and should eliminate the Trust Relationship issue. 
If you connect to GlobalProtect after then you should be able to install Matlab from there, provided you do not re-lock the computer.
You may also need to update the password in GlobalProtect to your most recent domain one. To do so you open GlobalProtect and under the settigns tab there should be a place to update your password.
Let us know if this works.

James Windorff

helpdesk-note.body:
Hello Eryn,
I swung by your office and it looks like you are stuck in lab until the end of the day.
Getting Office to activate is a little tricky but I can try to instruct you how to. Since it kept popping up even after entering the key I'm going to have you try a different approach.
1-Connect to the VPN by using Global Protect. If you don't have/don't know how to use this program you can find instructions here: https://community.msoe.edu/docs/DOC-1936 NOTE: If you need to install it, go to https://sslvpn.msoe.edu and download the 64 bit version for Windows.
2-Make sure you are hardwired into the MSOE network with an ethernet cable.
3-Open Outlook and when prompted to enter a license key enter: YC7DK-G2NP3-2QQC3-J6H88-GVGXT
It should then be able to activate Office.
Please let me know if this works or if it still refuses to.
Thank you! Abby Griffin
Issue: http://helpdesk.msoe.edu/helpdesk/tickets/6836
User called in for the office key popping issue
helpdesk-note.body-html:
Hello Eryn,

I swung by your office and it looks like you are stuck in lab until the end of the day.

Getting Office to activate is a little tricky but I can try to instruct you how to. Since it kept popping up even after entering the key I'm going to have you try a different approach.

1-Connect to the VPN by using Global Protect. If you don't have/don't know how to use this program you can find instructions here: https://community.msoe.edu/docs/DOC-1936
NOTE: If you need to install it, go to https://sslvpn.msoe.edu and download the 64 bit version for Windows.

2-Make sure you are hardwired into the MSOE network with an ethernet cable.

3-Open Outlook and when prompted to enter a license key enter: YC7DK-G2NP3-2QQC3-J6H88-GVGXT

It should then be able to activate Office.

Please let me know if this works or if it still refuses to.

Thank you!
Abby Griffin

Hi Mitch Colton, Issue: http://helpdesk.msoe.edu/helpdesk/tickets/6856
it appears that your account was simply locked out on Tuesday. This tend to happen when more than 4 bad passwords are logged from your account in a short period of time. Sometime this can be caused by email or wifi on devices are like phones or tablets, being logged into repeatedly. It appears that no bad passwords have been logged since then, so you should be good to go.
Have a nice day.

helpdesk-ticket.subject: User does not have access to printers.msoe.edu
helpdesk-ticket.description: Strange issue with a student's laptop. User is unable to install / access printers.msoe.edu. When I try to run \\printers or \\printers.msoe.edu, it fails and says that "The network path was not found." Troubleshooting steps in the notes.
helpdesk-ticket.description-html:
Strange issue with a student's laptop. User is unable to install / access printers.msoe.edu. When I try to run \\printers or \\printers.msoe.edu, it fails and says that "The network path was not found."
Troubleshooting steps in the notes.

helpdesk-note.body:
Troubleshooting steps:
restarted while connected to ethernet
noticed a couple more tunnel adapters than normal, ran 6to4remover.bat, it finished successfully, removed one tunnel adapter. Restarted.
Checked DNS settings on wireless and ethernet, both have correct settings.
Tried to access \\printers on both wireless, then ethernet. Both acted the same ("network path was not found").
successfully ping'd 8.8.8.8 and neo.msoe.edu. Could access get programs and internet.
Password is in good standing, and was not locked out while troubleshooting.
Is there any way there is a permissions issue with his account regarding printers.msoe.edu? Any other troubleshooting steps you guys need?
helpdesk-note.body-html:
Troubleshooting steps:

restarted while connected to ethernet

noticed a couple more tunnel adapters than normal, ran 6to4remover.bat, it finished successfully, removed one tunnel adapter. Restarted.

Checked DNS settings on wireless and ethernet, both have correct settings.

Tried to access \\printers on both wireless, then ethernet. Both acted the same ("network path was not  found").

successfully ping'd 8.8.8.8 and neo.msoe.edu. Could access get programs and internet. 

Password is in good standing, and was not locked out while troubleshooting.

Is there any way there is a permissions issue with his account regarding printers.msoe.edu? 
Any other troubleshooting steps you guys need?

helpdesk-note.body:
Please run the following commands on his laptop and send me the output
ipconfig /all
tracert printers.msoe.edu
Can you have him also see if he can access the network path from another computer
Thanks Mike

helpdesk-note.body:
I adjusted the power settings on the wireless AP in CC070 and in CC071 so that they don't overlap, but I doubt this was a problem. The AP in CC070 is the newest model running 802.11ac. The same model is used in the CC Great Room and in the Tower, and the config is universal across all of those models. I don't believe it's a config issue or we'd be seeing the same problem everywhere the new APs are mounted.
The user mentions break week, and we did re-enable authentication on MSOE wireless the week following break. If they made any changes, are not on the domain, or do not have their usernames in the wireless connection from prior to break, they should revisit those settings, or remove/forget and let the device re-detect.
Failing that, I can send someone down to test.
helpdesk-note.body-html:
